Ebrima Manneh was a Gambian journalist who disappeared after reporting critically on the government. His case highlights the dangers journalists and activists face under oppressive regimes where freedom of speech is limited. Enforced disappearances, surveillance, and intimidation are common risks for those exposing corruption or injustice.

For people in such situations, securing communications is crucial to avoid detection and protect themselves and their contacts. Using technologies that support encrypted, offline messaging and do not rely on internet connectivity can help prevent tracking and interception. Keywords to explore include journalistic freedom, forced disappearances, state surveillance, encrypted communication, and offline privacy tools.